SIMPLE: groom
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Groom
<hw>Groom</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. Scot.
<ets>grome</ets>, <ets>groyme</ets>, <ets>grume</ets>, <ets>gome</ets>,
<ets>guym</ets>, man, lover, OD. <ets>grom</ets> boy, youth; perh. the
<it>r</it> is an insertion as in E. <ets>bridegroom</ets>, and the word
is the same as AS. <ets>guma</ets> man. See <er>Bridegroom</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A boy or young man; a waiter; a servant; especially, a
man or boy who has charge of horses, or the stable.</def>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One of several officers of the English royal
household, chiefly in the lord chamberlain's department; <as>as, the
<ex>groom</ex> of the chamber; the <ex>groom</ex> of the
stole.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A man recently married, or about to be married; a
bridegroom.</def> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Groom porter</b></col>, <cd>formerly an officer in the
English royal household, who attended to the furnishing of the king's
lodgings and had certain privileges.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Groom</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Groom
<hw>Groom</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Groomed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Grooming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To tend or care for, or to curry
or clean, as a, horse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Groomer</ent>⟦br⟧
